    {
      "unresolved": true,
      "key": {
        "uuid": "3b87353a_3e731ccb",
        "filename": "librobinhood/src/plugins/ldiskfs/xattrs.c",
        "patchSetId": 9
      },
      "lineNbr": 135,
      "author": {
        "id": 1039247
      },
      "writtenOn": "2026-04-09T14:44:20Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "There seems to be none in the user header.\nThere is one in the source code:\n```\nvoid lustre_lma_swab(struct lustre_mdt_attrs *lma)\n{                                                                                \n#ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN                                                                 \n|   __swab32s(\u0026lma-\u003elma_compat);                                                 \n|   __swab32s(\u0026lma-\u003elma_incompat);                                                  \n|   lustre_swab_lu_fid(\u0026lma-\u003elma_self_fid);                                      \n#endif                                                                           \n}\n```\nThis does the same thing as my code but this would not work in the current code as the `\u003cendian.h\u003e` header I use (which provides `leXXtoh()` functions) defines `__BIG_ENDIAN` and `__LITTLE_ENDIAN` regardless of the cpu architecture, whereas lustre uses `\u003casm/byteorder.h\u003e` which only defines `__BIG_ENDIAN` or `__LITTLE_ENDIAN` depending on the architecture.\nI chose to do this because I believe `leXXtoh()` functions will make the code easier to read.",
      "parentUuid": "adb84000_c40dcb20",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 135,
        "startChar": 16,
        "endLine": 135,
        "endChar": 23
      },
